Bigdash aka Frank Starr approaches music playing contralto sax at the age of seven cultivating a passion for Jazz music. Today Frank Starr, already known in the musical scene as BigDash, is a DJ/producer who has been increasingly involved in the Milanese electronic scenario. Frank Starr plays deep-house and nu-disco at his parties and in the most interesting clubs of the city, alongside artists like Kenny Larkin, Shaun Reeves, and Buzz Goree during the Hush Parties.  
With the full development of Electronic music and particularly of Techno at the end of the 80s, Frank Starr conceives Music Priority, an artistic crew of friends and DJs with whom he begins to organize the very first well-known raves of the Tuscan scenario. In 2001, he records the EP Music Priority 001 for Urbanmantra Records, and thanks to the collaboration with Integrale Musique Ltd. his track “Junkie Tomato” is played by many of the European DJs of the moment. In 2003, he moves to Berlin with Pierantonio Gualtieri to reunite with Fraumutti, vocalist and instrumentalist on some new tracks. The work culminates in 2004 with the new label 11Numberecords and the making of two EPs: “King of Fools "(001) and "You Gotta Face It" (002). In 2007,  the Music Priority project consolidates, and with Caterina Donnini and Valentina Mutti Music Priority Cultural Association is founded. Today the Association is specialized in music events management  which involve not only the most significative crews of the city but also internationally-known DJs. In the same year, Frank Starr 
organizes the first edition of a festival which is happening contemporarily in all of Europe: “Festa della Musica”. In a few years, it becomes the most important event organized with Music Priority and today it has reached its eighth edition successfully. In 2010, with his associate Bonny Lester, he founds Activ8sounds Srl, for audio equipment services using the advanced sound system Funktion-One. In 2013, in concurrence with his new musical path, he begins a collaboration with Mixworks, Detroit label. The following year, Music Priority collaborates with Unconventional Events Srl and together they are looking at several projects to run, after bringing the first edition of Holi Dance Festival in Florence and Milan - the international colour festival - in the previous year.

Aside from his work as a DJ and promoter, Frank Starr actively works as a producer in his studio in Lambrate, Milan and has a long series of productions and multiple events in a program for the future.

DJ Anders - Delivering Joy of Life EDM

'techno / house / minimal / tech-house / progressive / melodic / groovy / bassy / happy / ... / danceable!'
 
FULL BIO: I have consumed music as long as I can remember. With the first 7” single bought from one of my weekly allowances as a kid – Abba “Waterloo” – my record collection started to build up. Starting out as a Radio DJ in secondary school, I soon got my first live gig 1983 in front of some hundreds of students at my school. Electronic music was early on, from “Pop Corn” with Hot Butter, via Jean Michel Jarre, to Kraftwerk and the full Synth Wave in early eighties.

From the moment I picked up Farley “Jackmaster” Funk with Love Can’t Turn Around most likely from the first import batch of that 12” Chicago House Classic in mid-Eighties, EDM has always been there in the crater. Totally hooked to “Joy of Life EDM” as I define it, I continue to spread the love vibes from the booth, with a contagious smile and energetic spread in full contact with the audience in high spirit. From the progressive sweaping meditative beats sliding over at the other side of the scale, via housy, techy, minimal and driving, groovy beats on the way, to the harder beats the longer into the night the set continues, they all fit in into my sets.

Feeling and dance-ability is more important than genre tag. EDM is constantly evolving, and so am I. 

I DJ with three aliases – DJ Anders (mostly focused on electronic dance music in a general sense as above, and here and there some retro/classics gigs), aBreathing (ambient and deep for relaxation, meditation and well-being) and rare occasions of Papa Abbie (roots reggae, dub and ska/two-tone, and the bassy flow of electronic dance music like dubstep/drum and bass). I also serve as a kind of “everydayness DJ”, with one so-called #daylist added almost daily, serving as a Music Diary / Soundtrack Of My Life – https://play.spotify.com/user/andersabrahamsson.

I love to mix the classics with the hot new tunage in a blend where I am closest to “Be the Change I want to See”, and living my vision RE:LOVE THE WORLD – “a world where you meet your fellow human being with Love and Respect, and can be expected to be met with the same”. My main in-real-world context is all things going on in the space related to NEMCOM - Norrköping Electronic Music Community.

See you on the dancefloor!

Peace, Anders

Born by the rice fields of Jennings, LA just west of the Mississippi River, Jacob Zachary let down his roots in the fertile land of the Deep South where his father was and still remains a preacher. Jacob’s greatest influences are the people and communities he grew up in and around. “Most places in the South are quite simple”, he says. “A man has either the temple or the tavern. He can choose his vices, or his sacraments, or both, but his heart will only ever have one song to sing.” Jacob’s music seeks out these songs in a way that determines to leave no stone unturned, no secret untold, and no one man blameless for any of it. The characters in his songs are from some older era in the South, where time was more slowly measured. They are Civil War soldiers, widows, murderers, and truck drivers, Their paths all converge in Jacob’s mind with stories to tell. They are stories of tortured souls longing for redemption, and begging at the ears of anyone who will listen. In Jacob’s wartime ballad “For The Love Of Sarah Pine”, the lyrics speak to this point in a spiritual way, from God’s perspective looking down on a mortally wounded Civil War soldier:

I prayed to God He said, “Child, you’ll never know me right/’til your eyes are dark enough to see my light./You keep searching through my heavens looking for some sign/but you’re talking to the wind boy/And you’re a dandelion

“I like to think my songs are about how and where most of our journey’s start – way down in the trenches reaching up to feel the light . The stories I tend to tell may not end with much hope, but it’s hope that inspires the telling.”

The Record Machine is a pioneering homegrown independent record label based in Kansas City, Missouri. The label was founded in 2003 when we released our first record for the James Dean Trio. In the 11 years since then we have worked with bands from all over the United States. Our current roster is Chambers, Stolen Nations, Ghastly Menace, Cowboy Indian Bear, La Guerre, Little Legend, Max Justus, The Noise FM, Palace, Spirit Is The Spirit, Soft Reeds, and State Bird. Our goal is to make an organic community of artists and help connect them with listeners. Tim Finn of The Kansas City Star remarked about The Record Machine’s output “[They] have assembled a stable of diverse artists who are making music that deserves national attention.”
